i=A.iX("Essential for Prelims and Mains. Memorize current RE capacity breakdown (solar/wind/hydro). PM-KUSUM scheme details and ISA are frequently tested.","",h,"","India has achieved a landmark milestone by crossing 190 GW of installed renewable energy capacity (including large hydro), reinforcing its position as one of the world's largest renewable energy producers.\n\nBreakdown of Renewable Energy Capacity:\n\u2022 Solar Power: 82 GW (largest contributor \u2014 43%)\n\u2022 Wind Power: 46 GW (24%)\n\u2022 Large Hydro: 47 GW (25%)\n\u2022 Small Hydro: 5 GW\n\u2022 Biomass & Others: 10 GW\n\nKey Targets:\n- 500 GW non-fossil fuel-based energy capacity by 2030 (announced at COP26)\n- 50% cumulative electric power from renewable sources by 2030\n- Solar capacity target: 300 GW by 2030\n- Wind capacity target: 140 GW by 2030\n\nPM-KUSUM Scheme:\n- Provides subsidies for solar pumps and grid-connected solar power plants for farmers\n- Target: 30.8 GW decentralized solar capacity through farmers\n- Helps farmers earn additional income by selling surplus power to DISCOMs\n\nInternational Solar Alliance (ISA):\nFounded by India and France in 2015, ISA now has 120+ member countries working to deploy solar energy solutions. India hosts ISA headquarters in Gurugram.\n\nInvestment:\nIndia attracted over $10 billion in renewable energy investments in the last fiscal year, making it the third most attractive renewable energy market globally after China and the USA.","",b,A.a(["National Solar Mission launched (2010)","ISA co-founded with France (2015)","COP26: 500 GW non-fossil target (2021)","PM-KUSUM: Solar pumps for farmers","Solar crosses 82 GW","Total RE reaches 190 GW","Target: 500 GW by 2030"],b8),"","a14","https://picsum.photos/seed/solar_india_renewable/800/400",!1,f,B.bZ,"RE-190: R=190 GW total, E=82 solar + 46 wind + 47 hydro; Target 500 by 2030; ISA=India+France=120 countries",a6,B.ag,g,e,i,"","India crosses 190 GW of installed renewable energy capacity, with solar becoming the largest contributor, as the country fast-tracks its 500 GW non-fossil fuel target for 2030.","","India Achieves Record Renewable Energy Capacity of 190 GW",a1)
